{"$ambrosia":"aero:interactive:9417ac60-5f60-11ea-8e69-affb2224d7e8:*","$id":"0a0cfda0-44e0-11ed-8f8a-3762284bc7f6","$workspaceId":"7fff47c0-44d6-11ed-bcef-d5307f42495c","$projectId":"86cb0040-44df-11ed-8442-dbcbc27803ca","annotations":[],"configSchemaVersion":"/pluginGenericSchema/v1","config":{"stage":{"sections":[{"rows":[{"columns":[{"stageElements":[{"type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"heading-two","ref":"67a10b63-1bd9-4ca6-bd4a-69b109e549c5","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Share Repurchases","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]}},"config":{"cssClass":""},"ref":"dbd0feec-0412-4383-b627-a8b304b71d89"},{"type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"adaf8062-0358-4ee7-9770-ebf9dd7574b3","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"An alternative way to pay cash to investors is through a share repurchase, also called a buyback. In this kind of transaction, the firm uses cash to buy shares of its own outstanding stock. These shares are generally held in the corporate treasury and they can be resold if the company needs to raise money in the future. We now examine three possible transaction types for a share repurchase.","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]}},"config":{"cssClass":""},"ref":"d0fac01e-c292-4497-856b-15b39983e172"},{"type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"heading-three","ref":"95d29ad0-2e34-4a68-b2ab-63e0be330144","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Open Market Repurchase","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]}},"config":{"cssClass":""},"ref":"eed53b0f-bc6c-4d04-ada0-fc3fa191d947"},{"type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"a0a99434-d7ba-478a-a161-06cc8ec2a583","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"With an ","marks":[]},{"data":{"ref":"eb489e96-2b17-4a22-b9d0-e1df9ac20714","stage":{"ref":"06358c1f-ef5d-44d1-ba59-a283f1bcbf5f","sections":[{"ref":"7828f166-8122-47a9-a5e5-3faa9dd964ab","rows":[{"ref":"9ef834e6-bb21-4a9e-8591-20190c650ff9","columns":[{"ref":"07fcf2d5-0240-4650-b1ed-fa46b4862c00","stageElements":[{"ref":"5a6e23b6-765b-4ece-ac7d-514e2c2460ae","type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"button","ref":"14fb5c6a-13c7-4d5b-8c55-ee621d4b4fcc","nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"4c5d1be6-e628-408b-aa10-f6046bff5c7f","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"When a firm repurchases its own shares by buying them on the open market over time.","marks":[]}],"data":{}}],"data":{}}]}}}]}]}]}]}},"nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"open market repurchase","marks":[]}],"object":"inline","type":"key-term","ref":"f2d5ff68-b928-4cf7-b4b6-122efd043043"},{"object":"text","text":", the most common way that firms repurchase shares, a firm announces its intention to buy its own shares on the open market and then proceeds to do so over time similar to any other investor. The firm may take a year or more to buy the shares and it is not obligated to repurchase the full amount it originally stated. Also, the firm must not buy its shares in a way that might appear to manipulate the price. For example, SEC guidelines recommend that the firm not purchase more than 25% of the average daily trading volume in its shares on a single day, nor make purchases at the market open or within 30 minutes of the close of trade.","marks":[]},{"data":{"ref":"26b10f31-d3de-4b5a-a1de-f94e2733dfcb","stage":{"ref":"5cb1ebf6-5270-405f-9190-210c003f17ea","sections":[{"ref":"b0d76676-9337-48a5-a861-c9d5ee4bf761","rows":[{"ref":"da5fe76b-9caa-4363-ba70-b63b469fef1c","columns":[{"ref":"3e736adf-108f-4457-82b7-f158e213bdcb","stageElements":[{"ref":"794f26e1-3547-4f86-a206-aaffd5471dc1","type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"button","ref":"b5333a4a-df31-4d90-b640-91add0a1e502","nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"4c07a68b-7bdb-4947-8c77-ec059f80444b","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"SEC Rule 10b-18, introduced in 1983, defines the guidelines for open market share repurchases.","marks":[]}],"data":{}}],"data":{}}]}}}]}]}]}]}},"nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"2","marks":[]}],"object":"inline","type":"footnote","ref":"629bb92b-194e-4792-bad5-a8d8731d56c4"}],"data":{}}]}},"config":{"cssClass":""},"ref":"98fcd547-f6bd-422c-9c6c-521ed9d2584d"},{"type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"a47f8f19-2b9f-4c5e-b71b-9e43a131f6b8","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"While open market share repurchases represent about 95% of all repurchase transactions,","marks":[]},{"data":{"ref":"e9f48a4d-9bc2-4cd9-b07e-efb79f976e0b","stage":{"ref":"99d60d2b-dc91-43f9-9cca-87021044dec1","sections":[{"ref":"ae485fd7-166f-4650-9c84-8a188b2ae8dc","rows":[{"ref":"96f0fa54-4982-46ac-933a-04645ef383b8","columns":[{"ref":"d18ad205-c3aa-4674-b067-745bb8b67db9","stageElements":[{"ref":"7b89f9c1-bce5-4b0d-a462-81501c93d909","type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"button","ref":"6b08b915-d7bd-4345-a313-864bad9bf372","nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"6d01e763-2bf0-46b9-a995-b3f66cfcb9a6","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"G. Grullon and D. Ikenberry, “What Do We Know About Stock Repurchases?” ","marks":[]},{"object":"text","text":"Journal of Applied Corporate Finance","marks":[{"type":"italic"}]},{"object":"text","text":" 13 (1) (2000): 31–51.","marks":[]}],"data":{}}],"data":{}}]}}}]}]}]}]}},"nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"3","marks":[]}],"object":"inline","type":"footnote","ref":"8e0356dd-1c1c-4fcd-9f28-9a232d5bf5cf"},{"object":"text","text":" other methods are available to a firm that wants to buy back its stock. These methods are used when a firm wishes to repurchase a substantial portion of its shares, often as part of a recapitalization.","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]}},"config":{"cssClass":""},"ref":"4df02df9-429c-492d-aa6f-40d735e8eb42"},{"type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"heading-three","ref":"02922d2d-0753-4294-aa7e-1db787dcc201","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Tender Offer","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]}},"config":{"cssClass":""},"ref":"e98a077e-7469-458a-9e61-3d2159b76eb2"},{"type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"0e7bdf88-0c78-4946-be5a-7b38716b2252","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"A firm can repurchase shares through a ","marks":[]},{"data":{"ref":"56994f99-2650-4dcb-9070-c7587f0833b9","stage":{"ref":"99ece4f6-8e95-4528-b35b-c70b9a57f440","sections":[{"ref":"b637cb14-6b5f-4a2a-a2bd-97c6abe10279","rows":[{"ref":"e3551a70-b63d-46b2-aad8-765630b42614","columns":[{"ref":"05775991-efee-4f21-a4ab-333f5a0cd6a5","stageElements":[{"ref":"98d46c5c-d6a4-4960-a57d-c370a2134d48","type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"button","ref":"4b93800f-01d7-467c-8259-a81826ac2733","nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"64c89b60-700c-4d81-a460-f19daac6fd37","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"A public announcement of an offer to all existing security holders to buy back a specified amount of outstanding securities at a prespecified price over a short time period, generally 20 days.","marks":[]}],"data":{}}],"data":{}}]}}}]}]}]}]}},"nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"tender offer","marks":[]}],"object":"inline","type":"key-term","ref":"b20467ae-6b54-4930-820a-306e4f6305e3"},{"object":"text","text":" in which it offers to buy shares at a prespecified price during a short time period, generally within 20 days. The price is usually set at a substantial premium (10%–20% is typical) to the current market price. The offer often depends on shareholders tendering a sufficient number of shares. If shareholders do not tender enough shares, the firm may cancel the offer and no buyback occurs.","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]}},"config":{"cssClass":""},"ref":"efb39308-412b-4231-bdc9-ac6e68fe9631"},{"type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"53d3b781-3cb9-47c4-87d7-058b4d17f7ba","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"A related method is the ","marks":[]},{"data":{"ref":"3240b15c-a606-4a35-9bad-62faf5d3b921","stage":{"ref":"0884dc88-988a-46e7-87d7-a09e2ccd2230","sections":[{"ref":"b7cb4f30-7cb7-4ae1-9d40-dbc8dedf2f1c","rows":[{"ref":"25e333ae-5db7-497f-82af-81c95fee4026","columns":[{"ref":"43007e5c-2c08-495c-914a-cc98a9a0bf2e","stageElements":[{"ref":"2dbcec12-b691-4b66-8133-377493e6d67a","type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"button","ref":"f3fe5f4b-e9f1-4401-827b-02e706356480","nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"014ec045-be98-4c93-bc08-45228c62a9ae","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Shareholders indicate prices and quantities of shares for sale. The firm pays the lowest possible price to repurchase its desired number of shares.","marks":[]}],"data":{}}],"data":{}}]}}}]}]}]}]}},"nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Dutch auction","marks":[]}],"object":"inline","type":"key-term","ref":"a5adbdf8-d593-482b-bc52-2d609d6e5c10"},{"object":"text","text":" share repurchase, in which the firm identifies a range of prices at which it is prepared to buy shares, and shareholders in turn indicate how many shares they are willing to sell at each price. The firm then pays the lowest price at which it can buy back its desired number of shares.","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]}},"config":{"cssClass":""},"ref":"f0aeb704-c018-4c17-a6f7-ef4760b363db"},{"type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"heading-three","ref":"115b2725-48c5-4b9e-b13a-78f424bfee8e","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Targeted Repurchase","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]}},"config":{"cssClass":""},"ref":"81d96743-6bfd-4d25-bfcc-89012011c6f3"},{"type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"8ec19bdb-83e4-4050-9b1a-1b43d044249d","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"A firm may also purchase shares directly from a major shareholder in a ","marks":[]},{"data":{"ref":"b0026729-7180-41ac-9617-36e6b8620813","stage":{"ref":"ccc331c8-1a56-45ee-a5aa-9accc2d13fa8","sections":[{"ref":"28b29f59-0ca5-4353-a784-eafb2af4bd6e","rows":[{"ref":"ad7be8d1-b8b7-47c3-8244-91ab10cc1fda","columns":[{"ref":"26a39141-c478-4734-ac86-95fbb472425c","stageElements":[{"ref":"c117cd50-6670-4114-be14-d3972b272d0b","type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"button","ref":"b32f5cc2-1bdf-4faa-956f-7cb484b1e611","nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"d8946ef2-9c4e-4cad-a6c7-ca90735dbf17","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"A firm purchases shares directly from a specific shareholder at a negotiated price.","marks":[]}],"data":{}}],"data":{}}]}}}]}]}]}]}},"nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"targeted repurchase","marks":[]}],"object":"inline","type":"key-term","ref":"c3c6dd84-c555-4a49-b95b-575b95a11f75"},{"object":"text","text":". In this case, the purchase price is negotiated directly with the seller. A targeted repurchase may occur if a major shareholder desires to sell a large number of shares but the market for the shares is not sufficiently liquid to sustain such a large sale without severely affecting the price. Under these circumstances, the shareholder may be willing to sell shares back to the firm at a discount to the current market price. Alternatively, targeted repurchases may be used if a major shareholder is threatening to take over the firm and remove its management. With ","marks":[]},{"data":{"ref":"bcc8ac0a-75e9-474b-98a4-5007252d16db","stage":{"ref":"1c066dbd-670e-43d8-acb7-25d771f2170f","sections":[{"ref":"ff2474c1-1484-4813-a45e-f303425f67f8","rows":[{"ref":"7170133b-2ecb-4444-b579-ad7d8ec93c2a","columns":[{"ref":"93f77779-8a8f-4955-947a-16bccfa0f2fb","stageElements":[{"ref":"9802440e-6358-4346-b9ea-3cf2a87f97b2","type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"button","ref":"a09233ff-3fef-42c5-aee8-104ef6e6cd5d","nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"67c6c0ae-a501-4c2a-b52f-f931337d5892","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"When a firm avoids takeover and removal of its management by a major shareholder by buying-out that shareholder, often at a premium.","marks":[]}],"data":{}}],"data":{}}]}}}]}]}]}]}},"nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"greenmail","marks":[]}],"object":"inline","type":"key-term","ref":"222fc8b6-f267-4704-ab2a-6e2024ba74b9"},{"object":"text","text":", the firm may decide to eliminate the threat by buying out the shareholder—often at a large premium over the current market price.","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]}},"config":{"cssClass":""},"ref":"3db2af5e-52a2-4373-b079-66c42354e1f1"}]}]}]},{"cssClass":"aside-group Sidebar_1Aside","rows":[{"columns":[{"stageElements":[{"type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"heading-two","ref":"1c04fd96-57f4-4d62-bb33-3e88356f0671","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Concept Check","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]}},"config":{"cssClass":""},"ref":"67ae161e-e17d-4992-bb10-2d36613c9400"